access management

Use the access management global configuration command to enable the access management. Use the no form of this command to disable the access management.

 

Syntax Description

access

Access management

management

Access management configuration

 

Default

The access management is disabled.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Enable the access management.

Example

This example shows how to enable the access management:

Switch(config)# access management

You can verify your settings by entering the show access management user EXEC command.

tcp-urg { < tcpv6_flag_urg> | any } ] ] } ] [ action { permit | deny | filter { switchport <filter_switch_port_list> | interface <port_type> [ <fliter_port_list> ] } } ] [ rate-limiter { <rate_limiter_id> | disable } ] [ mirror [ disable ] ] [ logging [ disable ] ] [ shutdown [ disable ] ] [ lookup-second [ disable ] ] [ redirect { switchport { <1-53> | <redirect_switch_port_list> } | interface { <port_type> <redirect_port_id> | <port_type> [ <redirect_port_list> ] } | disable } ]

Use the access-list ace global configuration command to set the access-list ace. The command without the update keywrod will creates or overwrites an existing ACE, any unspecified parameter will be set to its default value. Use the update keyword to update an existing ACE and only specified parameter are modified. The ACE must ordered by an appropriate sequence, the received frame will only be hit on the first matched ACE. Use the next or last keyword to adjust the ACE's sequence order.

Note1: There are a lot of parameters are depended on these features if supported on the platform. For example, The parameter of switch <SwitchID> and switchport {<SwitchPortId>|<SwitchPortList>} only support on stackable platform. The parameter of <port_type_id>, is used for ACLv1, <port_type_list>, action filter, tag, mirror, ipv6-icmp, ipv6-udp and ipv6-tcp is used for ACLv2. In stackable platform, the feature only supported for local interfaces. Use the parameter of redirect switchport for global ACE on stackable device.

Note2: The logging and shutdown features only works when the packet length is less than 1518(without VLAN tags).

 

Syntax Description

access-list

Access list

ace

Access list entry

update

Update an existing ACE

<ace_id>

ACE ID

next

insert the current ACE before the next ACE ID

<ace_id_next>

The next ID

last

Place the current ACE to the end of access list

ingress

Ingress

switch

Switch

<ingress_switch_id>

Switch ID

switchport

Switchport

<1-53>

<ingress_switch_port_list>

interface

<port_type>

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<ingress_port_id>

Port ID in the format of switch-no/port-no

<port_type>

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<ingress_port_list>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

access-list action { permit | deny }

Use the access-list action interface configuration command to configure access-list action. The access-list interface configuration will affect the received frames if it doesn't match any ACE.

access-list logging

Use the access-list logging interface configuration command to enable access-list logging. Use the no form of this command to disable access-list logging. The access-list interface configuration will affect the received frames if it doesn't match any ACE.

Note: The logging feature only works when the packet length is less than 1518(without VLAN tags).

alarm-level <alarm_level>

##HELP_MEP_ALARM_PRIO

 

Syntax Description

alarm-level

If a defect is detected with a priority higher than this level, a fault alarm notification will be generated.

<alarm_level>

A value of 1 will cause any defect to be reported as an alarm notification. A value of 6 will disable alarm notifications. See 802.1Q-2018, clause 20.9.5.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

CFM MEP Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_MEP_ALARM_PRIO

Example

None.

 

 

alarm-time-absent <alarm_time_absent_ms>

##HELP_MEP_ALARM_TIME_ABSENT

 

Syntax Description

alarm-time-absent

The time in milliseconds that defects must be absent before a fault alarm notification is reset. Default is 10000 ms.

<alarm_time_absent_ms>

##HELP_APS_SWITCH

 

Syntax Description

aps

Automatic Protection Switching

<inst>

APS instance number

switch

Request a switchover from the working path to the protection path or vice versa. Use 'aps <inst> clear' to clear the request.

force

Causes a switchover if no lockout is in effect

manual

Causes a switchover if the signal is good and no lockout is in effect

protect-to-working

Causes a manual signal switchover from the protection path to the working path if the protection path signal has not failed

working-to-protect

Causes a manual signal switchover from the working path to the protection path whether or not the working path signal is active or not

Example

This example shows how to clear ip dhcp snooping statistics:

Switch# clear ip dhcp snooping statistics

You can verify that the information was deleted by entering the show ip dhcp snooping statistics user EXEC command.

control-list index <index> gate-state { open | closed } time-interval <interval> { ms | us | ns } [ ipv <ipv> ] [ octet-max <octet_max> ]

Configures PSFP Admin Control List

 

Syntax Description

control-list

Configure Admin Control List

index

Specify index into the Gate Control List

<index>

Select an index into the Gate Control List. Only indices smaller than the configured control-list-length are allowed

gate-state

Configure Gate State

open

Open stream gate

closed

Close stream gate

time-interval

Configure Time Interval

<interval>

Set gate control entry's time interval (default is 1 nanosecond)

ms

Unit of time interval is milliseconds. With this unit, the interval cannot exceed 999 ms

us

Unit of time interval is microseconds. With this unit, the interval cannot exceed 999,999 us

ns

Unit of time interval is nanoseconds. With this unit, the interval cannot exceed 999,999,999 ns

ipv

Configure internal priority value. If left out, the IPV it has received so far will be kept

<ipv>

Select frame's internal priority value (egress queue).

octet-max

Configure the size of the largest frame that can slip through this gate. If left out, any-sized frame is allowed

<octet_max>

Size of the largest frame to let through gate. Use 0 to disable check

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

TSN Stream Gate Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

The time-interval cannot exceeed 999,999,999 nanoseconds.

Example

control-list index 1 gate-state open time-interval 1000 us ipv 4

File in USB, FLASH or on remote server. Syntax: <usb:filename> | <flash:filename> | <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]>. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

startup-config

Startup configuration

running-config

Currently running configuration

<destination_path>

File in USB, FLASH or on remote server. Syntax: <usb:filename> | <flash:filename> | <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]>. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

syntax-check

Perform syntax check on source configuration

save-host-key

Always save SSH host keys in local cache

ftp-active

Use active mode for FTP transfers (default is passive mode)

 

Default

None.

cycle-time <cycle_time> { ms | us | ns }

Set admin cycle time in units of either milliseconds (ms), microseconds (us) or nano seconds (ns)

 

Syntax Description

cycle-time

Set the gate's cycle time. A cycle time of up to 1 second can be specified

<cycle_time>

Set the gate's cycle time

ms

Set cycle time value in units of milliseconds. With this unit, the cycle time cannot exceed 1000 ms

us

Set cycle time value in units of microseconds. With this unit, the cycle time cannot exceed 1,000,000 us

ns

Set cycle time value in units of nanoseconds. With this unit, the cycle time cannot exceed 1,000,000,000 ns

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

TSN Stream Gate Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

The total cycle time cannot exceeed 1 second.

Example

cycle-time 100 ms

pause

Pause transmission of one or all single- or multi-frame flows initiated with 'debug frame tx'

resume

Resume transmission of one or all single- or multi-frame flows initiated with 'debug frame tx'

cancel

Cancel transmission of one or all single- or multi-frame flows initiated with 'debug frame tx'

print

Print frame as trace on a special trace group that is debug-enabled by default

all

All flows

<id>

Particular flow

force

debug critd { semaphore | mutex | recursive-mutex } { init | enter | exit | delete }

None.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

critd

Critical section

semaphore

Debug command for testing semaphores. You can create, enter or exit a semphore.

mutex

Debug command for testing mutexes. You can create, enter or exit a mutex.

recursive-mutex

Debug command for testing recursive mutexes. You can create, enter or exit a mutex.

init

Initiliaze a (recursive) mutex or a semaphore.

enter

Enters a (recursive) mutex or a semaphore. When you enter twice (without exiting) a deadlock will happen, and you will see a semaphore deadlock printout after a little while.

exit

Exits a (recursive) mutex or semaphore.

delete

Delete a (recursive) mutex or semaphore.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

debug firmware bootstrap <url_file> [ size <size> ] [ force ] [ save-host-key ] [ ftp-active ]

Use firmware bootstrap to bootstrap the switch. Default is to do nand bootstrap.

 

Syntax Description

debug

debug firmware

firmware

bootstrap

bootstrap

bootstrap a new switch

<url_file>

Uniform Resource Locator. It is a specific character string that constitutes a reference to a resource. Syntax: <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]/<file_name> If the following special characters: space !\"#$%&'()*+,/:;<=>?@[\\]^`{|}~ need to be contained in the input URL string, they should be percent-encoded. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

size

Specify a partition size

<size>

Size of data volume (in Mb). Default to max volume size.

force

force bootstrapping (Skip checks. Use only when ram loaded)

save-host-key

Always save SSH host keys in local cache

ftp-active

Use active mode for FTP transfers (default is passive mode)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Use to bootstrap the switch.

Example

debug firmware bootstrap tftp://10.10.10.10/new_image_path/new_image.img.mfi

debug frame tx [ interface <port_type> [ <plist> ] ] [ redbox-tag-disable ] [ redbox-dd-disable ] [ redbox-forward { port-a | port-b | both } ] [ { fph <fph> [ keep-paused ] } | { emix <emix> kbps <kbps> [ rate-type { line | data } ] [ keep-paused ] } ] [ packet-length <packet_length> ] [ dmac <dmac> ] [ smac <smac> ] [ otag vid <ovid> [ tpid <otpid> ] [ pcp <opcp> ] [ dei <odei> ] ] [ itag vid <ivid> [ tpid <itpid> ] [ pcp <ipcp> ] [ dei <idei> ] ] [ etype <etype> ] [ masquerade ] [ data <data1> <data2> <data3> <data4> ] [ payload { random | fixed <fixed_payload_value> } ]

None.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

frame

Frame function

tx

Transmit frame

interface

Optional port list. If this is not specified, the frame will be transmitted switched.

<port_type>

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<plist>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

redbox-tag-disable

Set RedBox Tag Disable flag in IFH

redbox-dd-disable

Set RedBox Duplicate Discard disable flag in IFH

redbox-forward

Set RedBox forward option in IFH

port-a

Set RedBox forward option to Port A

port-b

Set RedBox forward option to Port B

both

Set RedBox forward option to both Port A and Port B

fph

Inject frame periodically at a given frequency (frames per hour)

<fph>

Frames per hour

keep-paused

Send frame to H/W, but don't start the flow (mainly for debugging)

emix

Inject a sequence of frames periodically

<emix>

EMIX, that is, a string indicating the frame length and order of the individual frames. Lengths in bytes: 'a' = 64, 'b' = 128, 'c' = 256, 'd' = 512, 'e' = 1024, 'f' = 1280, 'g' = 1518, 'u' = Use 'packet-length'.

kbps

The sequence should take this number of kbps, which is either line or data rate, depending on rate-type.

<kbps>

Number of kilobits per second.

rate-type

Specify a rate-type. Defaults to 'line'

line

The kbps is specified in Layer1 (line) rate (default).

data

The kbps is specified in Layer2 (data) rate.

keep-paused

Send frames to H/W, but don't start the flow (mainly for debugging)

packet-length

Packet length, excluding FCS

<packet_length>

Bytes, excluding FCS

dmac

Destination MAC

<dmac>

MAC address

smac

Source MAC

<smac>

MAC address

otag

Specify an outer tag

vid

Specify Outer tag VLAN ID

<ovid>

Outer tag VLAN ID value

tpid

Specify outer tag TPID

<otpid>

Outer tag TPID (defaults to 0x88a8)

pcp

Specify outer tag PCP (defaults to 0)

<opcp>

Outer tag DEI value

dei

Specify outer tag DEI (defaults to 0)

<odei>

Outer tag DEI value

itag

Specify an inner tag

vid

Specify inner tag VLAN ID

<ivid>

Inner tag VLAN ID value

tpid

Specify inner tag TPID

<itpid>

Inner tag TPID (defaults to 0x8100)

pcp

Specify inner tag PCP (defaults to 0)

<ipcp>

Inner tag DEI value

dei

Specify inner tag DEI (defaults to 0)

<idei>

Inner tag DEI value

etype

Ether type

<etype>

Ether type

masquerade

The interface is the masquerade port number, i.e. the port number the frame pretends to ingress. The frame will be transmitted switched when specified

data

Specify first four bytes of data after ethertype. This will be filled after a possibly random/fixed payload

<data1>

Data byte #1

<data2>

Data byte #2

<data3>

Data byte #3

<data4>

Data byte #4

payload

Select what to fill payload with (default is random)

random

Fill with a random payload

fixed

Fill with a fixed value

<fixed_payload_value>

Fixed value to fill payload with

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<plist>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

packet-length

Packet length, excluding FCS. Defaults to 60 bytes.

<packet_length>

Bytes, excluding FCS

dmac

Destination MAC. Defaults to B/C if not specified.

<dmac>

MAC address

smac

Source MAC. Defaults to this switch's MAC address if not specified.

<smac>

MAC address

otag

Specify an outer tag

vid

Specify Outer tag VLAN ID

<ovid>

Outer tag VLAN ID value

tpid

Specify outer tag TPID

<otpid>

Outer tag TPID (defaults to 0x88a8)

pcp

Specify outer tag PCP (defaults to 0)

<opcp>

Outer tag DEI value

dei

Specify outer tag DEI (defaults to 0)

<odei>

Outer tag DEI value

itag

Specify an inner tag

vid

Specify inner tag VLAN ID

<ivid>

Inner tag VLAN ID value

tpid

Specify inner tag TPID

<itpid>

Inner tag TPID (defaults to 0x8100)

pcp

Specify inner tag PCP (defaults to 0)

<ipcp>

Inner tag DEI value

dei

Specify inner tag DEI (defaults to 0)

<idei>

Inner tag DEI value

sip4

Specify Source IPv4 address. Random of same type as DIP if not specified.

<sip4>

Source IPv4 address

sip6

Specify Source IPv6 address. Random of same type as SIP if not specified.

<sip6>

Source IPv6 address

dip4

Specify Destination IPv4 address. Random of same type as SIP if not specified.

<dip4>

Destination IPv4 address

dip6

Specify Destination IPv6 address. Random of same type as SIP if not specified.

<dip6>

Destination IPv6 address

dscp

Select DSCP value. Random if not specified.

<dscp>

DSCP value

dont-fragment

If specified, the DF bit in the IPv4 header gets set.

proto

Select IP protocol. If not specified, a random will be chosen.

tcp

Use TCP

udp

Use UDP

<ip_proto>

Specify IP protocol yourself

sport

Select IP protocol's source port. If not specified, a random will be chosen.

<sport>

Source port

dport

Select IP protocol's destination port. If not specified, a random will be chosen.

<dport>

Destination port

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

debug pagemap [ process-id <pid> ] [ { perm <perm> } | details ] [ changes-only ] [ section <section> ]

Dump this or a nother process' pagemap

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

pagemap

Show virtual address pagemap along with virtual and physical sizes

process-id

You may specify a process ID. If not, this application's process ID is used.

<pid>

Process ID to show

perm

Filter on section permissions.

<perm>

String that must be 4 chars long and contain the chars <r, w, x, p, s> at most once and <-, .> zero or more times. Use '.' as don't care. For example, use 'rw-.' to get read/writable data and '..x.' to get all executable sections. Default is '....'

details

Print all mapped pagemap entries from the item found in 'section' (exact match)

changes-only

Only show entries changed since last invokation of this command

section

Optional string containing the section name to find and display (exact match)

<section>

Optional string containing the section name to find and display, e.g. 'debug pagemap section [heap]'

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

debug phy-10g ckout [ { enable | disable } ] [ { use-squelch-src-as-is | invert-squelch-src } ] [ { Squelch-src <Squelch_src> } ] [ { full-rate-clk | div-by-2-clk } ] [ { clk-out-src <clk_out_src> } ]

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

phy-10g

10g Phy debug commands

ckout

Show or set CKOUT mode for Malibu 10Gphy

enable

Enable CKOUT

disable

Disable CKOUT

use-squelch-src-as-is

Use Squelch Source as is

invert-squelch-src

Invert Squelch Source

Squelch-src

Source of Auto Squelch Logic for CKOUT

<Squelch_src>

0-31: Various sources 32-63: Disable Squelch

full-rate-clk

Generate full-rate clock (i.e. LAN: 322.25MHz, WAN: 311.04MHz, 1G: 125MHz)

div-by-2-clk

Generate divide-by-2 version (i.e. LAN: 161.12MHz, etc)

clk-out-src

Select data to be transmitted from CKOUT pin (CKOUT SRC)

<clk_out_src>

0: Line 0 Transmit Clock 1: Line 1 Transmit Clock 2: Line 2 Transmit Clock 3: Line 3 Transmit Clock 4: Host 0 Transmit Clock 5: Host 1 Transmit Clock 6: Host 2 Transmit Clock 7: Host 3 Transmit Clock 8: Line 0 Recovered Clock 9: Line 1 Recovered Clock 10: Line 2 Recovered Clock 11: Line 3 Recovered Clock 12: Host 0 Recovered Clock 13: Host 1 Recovered Clock 14: Host 2 Recovered Clock 15: Host 3 Recovered Clock 16: Host Pll Clock 17: Line Pll Clock 18: CSR Clock 19: LTC Clock 20: Df2f clk 21: F2df clk 29: Debug 30: Debug 31: Oscillator output

 

Default

None.

Usage Guideline

debug phy-10g loopback [ { a | b | c | d | e | f | g | h | j | k | h2 | h3 | h4 | h5 | h6 | l0 | l1 | l2 | l3 | l2c } { enable | disable } ]

Show or set 10g phy loopback mode

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

phy-10g

10g Phy debug commands

loopback

Show or set 10g phy loopback mode

a

a: XFI -> XS -> XFI - deep

b

b: XAUI -> XS -> XAUI - shallow

c

c: XAUI -> XS -> XAUI - deep

d

d: XFI -> XS -> XFI - shallow

e

e: XAUI -> PCS FIFO -> XAUI

f

f: XFI -> PCS -> XFI (Venice equivalent: L2)

g

g: XAUI -> PCS -> XAUI (Venice equivalent: H3)

h

h: XFI -> WIS -> XFI

j

j: XAUI -> PMA -> XAUI (Venice equivalent: H4)

k

k: XFI -> PMA -> XFI

h2

Venice Host Loopback 2, 40-bit XAUI-PHY interface Mirror XAUI data

h3

Venice Host Loopback 3, 64-bit PCS after the gearbox FF00 repeating IEEE PCS system loopback

h4

Venice Host Loopback 4, 64-bit WIS FF00 repeating IEEE WIS system loopback

h5

Venice Host Loopback 5, 1-bit SFP+ after SerDes Mirror XAUI data IEEE PMA system loopback

h6

Venice Host Loopback 6, 32-bit XAUI-PHY interface Mirror XAUI data

l0

Venice Line Loopback 0, 4-bit XAUI before SerDes Mirror SFP+ data

l1

Venice Line Loopback 1, 4-bit XAUI after SerDes Mirror SFP+ data IEEE PHY-XS network loopback

l2

Venice Line Loopback 2, 64-bit XGMII after FIFO Mirror SFP+ data

l3

Venice Line Loopback 3, 64-bit PMA interface Mirror SFP+ data

l2c

Malibu Line Loopback l2c, 64-bit XGMII interface Mirror SFP+ data

enable

Enable loopback

disable

Disable loopback

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

debug phy-10g loopback a enable

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

phy-10g

10g Phy debug commands

synce

Show or Set SyncE modes on 10G PHY.

mode

Synchronous ethernet modes

<mode>

3:LAN 4:WAN 5 : Mixed mode, channel being configured in LAN mode and other is in WAN mode 6 : Mixed mode, channel being configured in WAN mode and other is in LAN mode

clk-out

Recovered clocks used from phy

<clk_out>

0 : RXCLKOUT 1 : TXCLKOUT

hitless

Clock synthesizer is hitless or not

<hitless>

0 : External Clock synthesizer is not hitless, SREFCLK and XREFCLK used as input Clock 1 : External Clock synthesizer is hitless, XREFCLK is used as input Clock

rclk-div

Recovered Clock's divisor

<rclk_div>

0 : Recovered clock is divided by 64 1 : Recovered clock is divided by 66

sref-div

SREFCLK's divisor

<sref_div>

0 : SREFCLK is divided by 64 1 : SREFCLK is divided by 66 2 : SREFCLK is divided by 16

wref-div

WREFCLK's divisor

<wref_div>

0 : WREFCLK/16 is not used 1 : WREFCLK/16 is used

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

debug port-security rate-limit { [ fill-level-min <fill_level_min> ] [ fill-level-max <fill_level_max> ] [ rate <rate> ] [ drop-age <drop_age> ] }

None.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

port-security

Port Security

rate-limit

Rate limiter

fill-level-min

Hysteresis: after the burst capacity has been reached, do not allow new frames until it reaches this amount

<fill_level_min>

Minimum number of frames

fill-level-max

Burst capacity. At most this amount of frames in a burst

<fill_level_max>

Maximum number of frames

rate

At most this amount of frames per second over time (better to pick a power-of-two for this number)

<rate>

Number of frames per second

drop-age

Drop the frame if it is less than this amount of milliseconds since last frame with this MAC address was seen

<drop_age>

Number of milliseconds

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

debug show snmp mib redefine

Use the show snmp mib redefine user EXEC command to display the redefined MIBs in the switch, that are different definitions from the standard MIBs.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Show running system information

show

SNMP (Simple Network Management Protocol)

snmp

MIB (Management Information Base)

mib

The different definitions from the standard MIBs

redefine

None.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Expressions are case sensitive. For example, if you enter | exclude output, the lines that contain output do not appear, but the lines that contain Output appear.

Example

This is an example of output from the show snmp mib redefine command:

Switch# show snmp mib redefine

Object Syntax Access Redefine Access Redefine Size

---------------------------------- --------- ---------- --------------- -------------

SNMP-USER-BASED-SM-MIB :

usmUserPublic OCTET_STR read-create read-only

usmUserStorageType INTEGER read-create read-only {4 permanent}

usmUserStatus INTEGER read-create read-only {1 active}

debug vlan port-type interface <port_type> [ <plist> ] { static | dot1x | mvr | voice-vlan | mstp | erps | mrp | vcl | gvrp | rmirror } { unaware | c-port | s-port | s-custom-port }

None.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

vlan

Virtual LAN

port-type

Port type

interface

Port interface

<port_type>

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<plist>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

static

Static user

dot1x

NAS user

mvr

MVR user

voice-vlan

Voice VLAN user

mstp

MSTP user

erps

ERPS user

mrp

MRP user

vcl

VCL user

gvrp

GVRP user

rmirror

RMirror user

unaware

On ingress, all frames, whether carrying a VLAN tag or not, get classified to the Port VLAN, and possible tags are not removed on egress

c-port

On ingress, frames with a VLAN tag with TPID = 0x8100 get classified to the VLAN ID embedded in the tag. If a frame is untagged or priority tagged, the frame gets classified to the Port VLAN. If frames must be tagged on egress, they will be tagged with a C-tag

s-port

On ingress, frames with a VLAN tag with TPID = 0x8100 or 0x88A8 get classified to the VLAN ID embedded in the tag. If a frame is untagged or priority tagged, the frame gets classified to the Port VLAN. If frames must be tagged on egress, they will be tagged with an S-tag

s-custom-port

On ingress, frames with a VLAN tag with a TPID = 0x8100 or equal to the EtherType configured for Custom-S ports get classified to the VLAN ID embedded in the tag. If a frame is untagged or priority tagged, the frame gets classified to the Port VLAN. If frames must be tagged on egress, they will be tagged with the custom S-tag.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

debug vlan tx-tag interface <port_type> [ <plist> ] { static | dot1x | mvr | voice-vlan | mstp | erps | mrp | vcl | gvrp | rmirror } { tag-this <tag_vid> | untag-this <untag_vid> | tag-all | untag-all }

None.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

vlan

Virtual LAN

tx-tag

Set Tx tag type for volatile VLAN user

interface

Port interface

<port_type>

Port type in Fast, Giga or Tengiga ethernet

<plist>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

static

Static user

dot1x

NAS user

mvr

MVR user

voice-vlan

Voice VLAN user

mstp

MSTP user

erps

ERPS user

mrp

MRP user

vcl

VCL user

gvrp

GVRP user

rmirror

RMirror user

tag-this

Frames classified to the Port VLAN are transmitted tagged. Other frames are transmitted without tag.

<tag_vid>

Port VLAN

untag-this

Frames classified to the Port VLAN are transmitted untagged. Other frames are transmitted with the relevant tag.

<untag_vid>

Port VLAN

tag-all

All frames, whether classified to the Port VLAN or not, are transmitted with a tag.

untag-all

All frames, whether classified to the Port VLAN or not, are transmitted without a tag.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

debug voice vlan { lldp [ interface <port_type> [ <port_list> ] ] | capability }

Use the debug voice vlan debug command to display the MAC telephony entries of Voice VLAN which learn from LLDP or the module capabilities.

 

Syntax Description

debug

Debugging functions

Voice appliance attributes

vlan

VLAN for voice traffic

lldp

LLDP

Select an interface to configure

<port_type>

<port_list>

List of Port ID, ex, 1/1,3-5;2/2-4,6

capability

Display Voice VLAN Capabilities

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Display the MAC telephony entries of Voice VLAN which learn from LLDP.

Example

This example shows how to display the MAC telephony entries of Voice VLAN:

Switch# debug voice vlan lldp

MAC Address Interface

----------- ---------

00-00-00-00-00-01 Giga 1/1

00-00-00-00-00-02 Giga 1/1

default access-list rate-limiter [ <rate_limiter_list> ]

Use the default access-list rate-limiter global configuration command to restore the default setting of access-list rate-limiter.

 

Syntax Description

default

Set a command to its defaults

access-list

Access list

rate-limiter

Rate limiter

<rate_limiter_list>

Rate limiter ID

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Restore the default setting of access-list rate-limiter.

Example

This example shows how to restore the default setting on all rate-limiter IDs:

Switch(config)# default access-list rate-limiter

You can verify your settings by entering the show access-list rate-limiter privileged EXEC command.

 

 

default range { all | <range_name> }

Set the filtering rule in an IPMC profile as default condition, that is, default it to not logging and deny the address range.

 

Syntax Description

default

Set a command to its defaults

range

A range of IPv4/IPv6 multicast addresses for the profile

all

Default all rules in this profile

<range_name>

Default this particular rule

 

Default

No log capability and deny matching addresses

Command Mode

IPMC Profile Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When you are in IPMC profile configuration mode, use default range command to make a specific filtering rule working in default conditions.

Example

This example shows when and how to execute default range command in ipmc profile configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

dmac { <dmac_addr> [ / <dmac_mask> ] | multicast | broadcast | unicast | not-broadcast | not-unicast | any }

None.

 

Syntax Description

dmac

Specify a destination MAC to match against incoming frames

<dmac_addr>

A destination MAC address to match against incoming frames

/

Specify a mask. If no mask is specified, all bits of the destination MAC address shall match the incoming frame

<dmac_mask>

A mask in the form xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx, that specifies which bits of the destination MAC address that shall match the incoming frames. Default is to match all 48 bits

multicast

Match any multicast destination MAC address (excluding broadcast)

broadcast

Match the broadcast destination MAC address

unicast

Match any unicast MAC address

not-broadcast

Match any MAC address, except the broadcast MAC address

not-unicast

Match any multicast or the broadcast destination MAC address

any

Match any destination MAC address

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

##DOT1X_GUEST_VID_HELP

IEEE Standard for port-based Network Access Control

<value>

Guest VLAN ID used when entering the Guest VLAN.

 

Default

Global Configuration Mode

dot1x guest-vlan supplicant

##DOT1X_GUEST_VLAN_SUPPLICANT_HELP

 

Syntax Description

dot1x

IEEE Standard for port-based Network Access Control

guest-vlan

Guest VLAN

supplicant

The switch remembers if an EAPOL frame has been received on the port for the life-time of the port. Once the switch considers whether to enter the Guest VLAN, it will first check if this option is enabled or disabled. If disabled (unchecked, default), the switch will only enter the Guest VLAN if an EAPOL frame has not been received on the port for the life-time of the port. If enabled (checked), the switch will consider entering the Guest VLAN even if an EAPOL frame has been received on the port for the life-time of the port.

 

Default

supplicant is disabled.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##DOT1X_GUEST_VLAN_SUPPLICANT_HELP

Example

dot1x guest-vlan supplicant

##HELP_ERPS_SWITCH

erps

ERPS instance number

fec { auto | r-fec | rs-fec | none }

Use this command to force a particular FEC mode.

 

Syntax Description

fec

Control Forward Error Correction

auto

Let the switch application decide which FEC (if any) to enable based on port and SFP transceiver type.

r-fec

Force-enable R-FEC (Firecode Forward Error Correction, 802.3by clause 74).

rs-fec

Force-enable RS-FEC (Reed-Solomon Forward Error Correction, 802.3by clause 108).

none

Do not use FEC. If using 802.3 clause 73 to negotiate speed, FEC may get enabled anyway if link partner requests it.

 

Default

'fec auto' is default and tells the switch application to combine the SFP and port type to find a suitable FEC to use - if any.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Use this command to force a particular FEC mode.

Example

'fec r-fec'

 

 

firmware swap

firmware upgrade <url_file> [ save-host-key ] [ ftp-active ]

Use firmware upgrade to load new firmware image to the switch.

 

Syntax Description

firmware

Firmware upgrade/swap

upgrade

Firmware upgrade

<url_file>

Uniform Resource Locator. It is a specific character string that constitutes a reference to a resource. Syntax: <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]/<file_name> If the following special characters: space !\"#$%&'()*+,/:;<=>?@[\\]^`{|}~ need to be contained in the input URL string, they should be percent-encoded. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

save-host-key

Always save SSH host keys in local cache

ftp-active

Use active mode for FTP transfers (default is passive mode)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Use to load new firmware image to the switch.

Example

firmware upgrade tftp://10.10.10.10/new_image_path/new_image.dat

hsr-mode { h | n | t | u | m | r }

##HELP_REDBOX_HSR_MODE

 

Syntax Description

hsr-mode

Select the HSR mode to run the RedBox in (not available in PRP-SAN mode).

h

HSR LRE bridges HSR-tagged traffic

n

Bridging between HSR ports is disabled

t

Transparent forwarding. Bridging occurs without HSR tag

u

Unicast forwarding. As Mode H, but also forwards traffic for which this RedBox is the unique destination

m

HSR LRE is configured in mixed mode (HSR-tagged frames forwarded as in MODE H, HSR-untagged frames forwarded according to 802.1Q)

r

BPDUs are encapsulated/decapsulated and forwarded to avoid HSR ring short-circuits a STP topology

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Redbox Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_REDBOX_HSR_MODE

Example

None.

inner-tag { none | vid { { <vid> [ / <vid_mask> ] | any } [ pcp <pcp_val> [ / <pcp_mask> ] ] [ dei <dei_val> ] [ { c-tag | s-tag } ] } }

None.

 

Syntax Description

inner-tag

Configuration of an inner tag to match against incoming frames

none

There must be no inner tag

vid

The frame must be double-tagged. The next keyword tells whether all VLANs are matched or only a specific with an optional mask

<vid>

VLAN ID to match incoming frames against

/

A mask specified as an integer, that specifies which bits of the VLAN ID that shall match the incoming frames

<vid_mask>

A mask specified as an integer, that specifies which bits of the VID that shall match the incoming frames

any

Match any incoming VLAN ID

pcp

Configuration of a PCP value to match against incoming frames

<pcp_val>

The PCP value to match the incoming frames against

/

Configuration of a mask. If no mask is specified, all bits of the PCP value shall match the incoming frame

<pcp_mask>

A mask that specifies the bits of the PCP value that shall match the incoming frame

dei

Specify a DEI value to match the incoming frame against

<dei_val>

The DEI value that shall match the incoming frame

c-tag

If specified, only match C-tagged frames (EtherType = 0x8100)

s-tag

If specified, only match S-tagged frames (EtherType = 0x88a8)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

ip dhcp relay information option

Use the ip dhcp relay information option global configuration command to enable the DHCP relay information option. Use the no form of this command to disable the DHCP relay information option.

The option 82 circuit ID format as "[vlan_id][module_id][port_no]". The first four characters represent the VLAN ID, the fifth and sixth characters are the module ID(in standalone device it always equal 0, in stackable device it means switch ID), and the last two characters are the port number. For example, "00030108" means the DHCP message receive form VLAN ID 3, switch ID 1, port No 8. And the option 82 remote ID value is equal the switch MAC address.

 

Syntax Description

ip

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

dhcp

Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol

relay

DHCP relay agent configuration

information

DHCP information option (Option 82)

option

DHCP option

 

Default

The DHCP relay information option is disabled.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Enable the DHCP relay information option.

Example

This example shows how to enable the DHCP relay information option:

Switch(config)# ip dhcp relay information option

You can verify your settings by entering the show ip dhcp relay user EXEC command.

 

 

ip dhcp relay information policy { drop | keep | replace }

Use the ip dhcp relay information policy global configuration command to configure the DHCP relay information policy.

When DHCP relay information mode operation is enabled, if the agent receives a DHCP message that already contains relay agent information it will enforce the policy. The 'Replace' policy is invalid when relay information mode is disabled.

 

Syntax Description

ip

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

dhcp

Dynamic Host Configuration Protocol

relay

DHCP relay agent configuration

information

DHCP information option (Option 82)

policy

Policy for handling the receiving DHCP packet already include the information option

drop

Drop the package when receive a DHCP message that already contains relay information

keep

Keep the original relay information when receive a DHCP message that already contains it

replace

Replace the original relay information when receive a DHCP message that already contains it

 

Default

The DHCP relay information policy is keep the original DHCP information.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Configure the DHCP relay information policy.

Example

This example shows how to configure the DHCP relay information drop policy:

Switch(config)# ip dhcp relay information policy drop

You can verify your settings by entering the show ip dhcp relay user EXEC command.

ip http secure-certificate { upload <url_file> [ pass-phrase <pass_phrase> ] | delete | generate }

Use the ip http secure-certificate global configuration command to manage the HTTPS certificate(PEM format).

 

Syntax Description

ip

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

http

Hypertext Transfer Protocol

secure-certificate

HTTPS certificate

upload

Upload a certificate PEM file

<url_file>

Uniform Resource Locator. It is a specific character string that constitutes a reference to a resource. Syntax: <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]/<file_name> If the following special characters: space !\"#$%&'()*+,/:;<=>?@[\\]^`{|}~ need to be contained in the input URL string, they should be percent-encoded. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

pass-phrase

Pass phrase

<pass_phrase>

Privacy key pass phrase string

delete

Delete the current certificate

generate

Generate a new self-signed RSA certificate

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Example

This example shows how to upload the HTTPS certificate from TFTP server:

(config)# ip http secure-certificate upload tftp://10.9.52.103/test_ca.pem

You can verify your settings by entering the show ip http privileged EXEC command.

...

ip ospf authentication-key { unencrypted <unencrypted_pwd> | encrypted <encrypted_pwd> }

None.

 

Syntax Description

ip

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

ospf

Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)

authentication-key

Configure simple password authentication

unencrypted

Specifies an UNENCRYPTED password will follow

<unencrypted_pwd>

The UNENCRYPTED (Plain Text) user password. Any printable characters including space is accepted. Notice that you have no chance to get the Plain Text password after this command. The system will always display the ENCRYPTED password.

encrypted

Specifies an ENCRYPTED password will follow

<encrypted_pwd>

The ENCRYPTED (hidden) user password. Notice the ENCRYPTED password will be decoded by system internally. You cannot directly use it as same as the Plain Text and it is not human-readable text normally.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

VLAN Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

ip ospf { priority <priority> | cost <cost> | mtu-ignore | hello-interval <hello_interval> | retransmit-interval <retransmit_interval> | dead-interval { <dead_interval> | minimal hello-multiplier <fast_hello_packets> } }

None.

 

Syntax Description

ip

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

ospf

Open Shortest Path First (OSPF)

priority

Set OSPF router priority for the specific interface.

<priority>

User specified router priority for the interface.

cost

Set OSPF link state metric for the interface. It is used for Shortest Path First (SPF) calculation.

<cost>

User specified cost for the interface.

mtu-ignore

Ignore Interface MTU received in Database Description packets.

hello-interval

Set the hello-interval value for the specific interface.

<hello_interval>

User hello-interval value for the specific interface.

retransmit-interval

Set the retransmit-interval value for the specific interface. It's the time interval (in seconds) to wait before retransmitting a database description packet or a link-state request when it has not been acknowledged.

<retransmit_interval>

User retransmit-interval value for the specific interface.

dead-interval

Set the dead-interval value (number of seconds) for the specific interface.

<dead_interval>

User dead-interval value for the specific interface.

minimal

None.

hello-multiplier

None.

<fast_hello_packets>

None.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

VLAN Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

ipmc profile

Enable IPMC profile filtering globally

 

Syntax Description

ipmc

IPv4/IPv6 multicast configuration

profile

Enable or disable (with the no-form) IPMC profile filtering globally

 

Default

IPMC profile filtering is disabled by default

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When the IPMC profile filtering is required, use this command to enable the profile filtering.

Example

This example shows how to execute ipmc profile command in global configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# do show running-config all-defaults

...

!

no ipmc profile

!

...

Switch(config)# ipmc profile

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc profile

!

...

ipmc range <range_name> { <ipv4_start> [ <ipv4_end> ] | <ipv6_start> [ <ipv6_end> ] }

Create or update an IPMC profile range entry

 

Syntax Description

ipmc

IPv4/IPv6 multicast configuration

range

A range of IPv4/IPv6 multicast addresses for the profile

<range_name>

Name of range (1-16 characters in ASCII range [33-126]. Cannot be 'all' (case-insensitively))

<ipv4_start>

Valid IPv4 multicast address

<ipv4_end>

Valid IPv4 multicast address that is not less than start address

<ipv6_start>

Valid IPv6 multicast address

<ipv6_end>

Valid IPv6 multicast address that is not less than start address

 

Default

None

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When the IPMC profile address range is required, use this command to configure the profile address range.

Example

This example shows how to execute ipmc range command in global configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# exit

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

...

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.1.0.0

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.1.0.0

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

...

 

 

ipv <ipv>

Set admin internal priority value to be used when no gate control list is executing

 

Syntax Description

ipv

Set admin internal priority value

<ipv>

Set frame's initial internal priority value (egress queue). May be overridden by a control list entry later

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

TSN Stream Gate Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

ipv 3

 

 

ipv4 [ sip { <sip> | any } ] [ dip { <dip> | any } ] [ dscp { <dscp_vr> | { be | af11 | af12 | af13 | af21 | af22 | af23 | af31 | af32 | af33 | af41 | af42 | af43 | cs1 | cs2 | cs3 | cs4 | cs5 | cs6 | cs7 | ef | va } | any } ] [ fragment { yes | no | any } ] [ proto { <proto_value> | tcp | udp | any } ] [ dport { <dport_vr> | any } ]

None.

 

Syntax Description

ipv4

Match IPv4 frames

sip

Match on source IPv4 address

<sip>

Match on source IPv4 address/mask, e.g. 1.2.3.4/32 or 1.2.0.0/16

any

Match on any source IPv4 address

dip

Match on destination IPv4 address

<dip>

Match on destination IPv4 address/mask, e.g. 1.2.3.4/32 or 1.2.0.0/16

any

Match on any destination IPv4 address

dscp

Match on DSCP

<dscp_vr>

Matched DSCP value/range (e.g. 17-33 or 17)

be

Default PHB (DSCP 0) for best effort traffic

af11

Assured Forwarding PHB AF11 (DSCP 10)

af12

Assured Forwarding PHB AF12 (DSCP 12)

af13

Assured Forwarding PHB AF13 (DSCP 14)

af21

Assured Forwarding PHB AF21 (DSCP 18)

af22

Assured Forwarding PHB AF22 (DSCP 20)

af23

Assured Forwarding PHB AF23 (DSCP 22)

af31

Assured Forwarding PHB AF31 (DSCP 26)

af32

Assured Forwarding PHB AF32 (DSCP 28)

af33

Assured Forwarding PHB AF33 (DSCP 30)

af41

Assured Forwarding PHB AF41 (DSCP 34)

af42

Assured Forwarding PHB AF42 (DSCP 36)

af43

Assured Forwarding PHB AF43 (DSCP 38)

cs1

Class Selector PHB CS1 precedence 1 (DSCP 8)

cs2

Class Selector PHB CS2 precedence 2 (DSCP 16)

cs3

Class Selector PHB CS3 precedence 3 (DSCP 24)

cs4

Class Selector PHB CS4 precedence 4 (DSCP 32)

cs5

Class Selector PHB CS5 precedence 5 (DSCP 40)

cs6

Class Selector PHB CS6 precedence 6 (DSCP 48)

cs7

Class Selector PHB CS7 precedence 7 (DSCP 56)

ef

Expedited Forwarding PHB (DSCP 46)

va

Voice Admit PHB (DSCP 44)

any

Match any DSCP

fragment

Setup matching on IPv4 fragments

yes

Match IPv4 headers with MF bit set or a fragment offset > 0

no

Match IPv4 headers with MF bit cleared and fragment offset 0

any

Match any values of IPv4 header's MF bit and fragment offset value

proto

Match on IP protocol

<proto_value>

Match a custom IP protocol number

tcp

Match TCP frames (protocol number 6)

udp

Match UDP frames (protocol number 17)

any

Match any IP protocol

dport

Setup matching on UDP/TCP destination port

<dport_vr>

Match UDP/TCP destination port value/range (e.g. 123-345 or 123)

any

Match any UDP/TCP destination port

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

Syntax Description

ipv6

Interface Internet Protocol configuration commands

ospf

Open Shortest Path First for IPv6 (OSPFv3)

passive

Set the interface as passive

priority

Set OSPF6 router priority for the specific interface.

<priority>

User specified router priority for the interface.

cost

Set OSPF6 link state metric for the interface. It is used for Shortest Path First (SPF) calculation.

<cost>

User specified cost for the interface.

mtu-ignore

Ignore Interface MTU received in Database Description packets.

hello-interval

Set the hello-interval value for the specific interface.

<hello_interval>

User hello-interval value for the specific interface.

retransmit-interval

Set the retransmit-interval value for the specific interface. It's the time interval (in seconds) to wait before retransmitting a database description packet or a link-state request when it has not been acknowledged.

<retransmit_interval>

User retransmit-interval value for the specific interface.

transmit-delay

Set the transmit-delay value for the specified interface

<transmit_delay>

User transmit-delay value for the specified interface

dead-interval

Set the dead-interval value (number of seconds) for the specific interface.

<dead_interval>

User dead-interval value for the specific interface.

Duration of the monitoring in terms of seconds

<error_window>

Set window size in terms of seconds

threshold

Number of permissible error symbols in the period defined by the error window

<error_threshold>

Threshold in number of symbols

 

Default

Default for error window 1 second,for threshold 0 symbols.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

link-oam link-monitor symbol-period window 20 threshold 10

lldp med type { connectivity | end-point }

##LLDP_ENDPOINT_HELP

 

Syntax Description

lldp

Link Layer Discover Protocol.

med

Media Endpoint Discovery.

type

Select if the interface is working as 'Network Connectivity Device' or an 'Endpoint Device'. The difference between working as 'Network Connectivity Device' and an 'Endpoint Device' is a question of who is initializing the LLDP-MED TLVs transmission. A 'Network Connectivity Device' is not starting LLDP-MED TLVs transmission until it has detected an 'Endpoint Device' as link partner. An 'Endpoint Device' will start LLDP-MED TLVs transmission at once.

connectivity

Work as connectivity device.

end-point

Work as end-point device.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

<on_startup_interval>

User specified the time interval (seconds) to advertise itself as stub area

on-shutdown

Configures OSPF to advertise a maximum metric during shutdown for a configured period of time. The device advertises a maximum metric when the OSPF router mode is disabled and notice that the mechanism also works when the device reboots but not for the 'reload default' case.

<on_shutdown_interval>

User specified the time interval (seconds) to wait till shutdown completed

administrative

mode { 1-for-1 | bidirectional-1-plus-1 | unidirectional-1-plus-1 [ tx-aps ] }

##HELP_APS_MODE

 

Syntax Description

mode

Specify the APS' architecture and direction

1-for-1

1:1, that is, source determines which port traffic goes into.

bidirectional-1-plus-1

Bidirectional 1+1, that is, traffic goes into both ports, and sink selects based on local defects and APS PDUs received from the far end.

unidirectional-1-plus-1

Unidirectional 1+1, that is, traffic goes into both ports, and sink selects exclusively based on local defects.

tx-aps

Transmit APS PDUs even in unidirectional 1+1. Reception of APS PDUs in this mode are only used for informational purposes.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

APS Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_APS_MODE

Example

None.

more

Display file

<path>

File in USB, FLASH or on remote server. Syntax: <usb:filename> | <flash:filename> | <protocol>://[<username>[:<password>]@]<host>[:<port>][/<path>]>. A valid file name is a text string drawn from alphabet (A-Za-z), digits (0-9), dot (.), hyphen (-), under score (_). The maximum length is 63 and hyphen must not be first character. The file name content that only contains '.' is not allowed.

None.

None.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Alternatively you can simply configure some of the MRP timers while leaving the rest unchanged.

Switch(config-if)# mrp timers leave-time 80

Configure the MVRP VLAN list.

Example

This example shows how to configure a list of MVRP-managed VLANs.

Switch(config)# mvrp managed vlan 1-100,200

Alternatively you can simply enable MVRP on all VLANs.

Switch(config)# mvrp managed vlan all

You can also edit the existing list by adding or removing VLANs.

Switch(config)# mvrp managed vlan add 300

Switch(config)# mvrp managed vlan remove 50

Finally, enable MVRP on all VLANs, excluding a given set.

Switch(config)# mvrp managed vlan except 1-3,10

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

 

 

no area <area_id> nssa [ translate type7 { candidate | never | always } | no-summary ]

None.

 

Syntax Description

no

Negate a command or set its defaults

area

OSPF area ID

<area_id>

The OSPF area ID can be specified as either an IPv4 address format(A.B.C.D) or a decimal value from 0 to 4294967295.

nssa

Configure the area as a nssa

translate

Translate LSA

type7

From Type 7 to Type 5

candidate

Configure NSSA-ABR for translate election (default)

never

Configure NSSA-ABR to never translate

always

Configure NSSA-ABR to always translate

no-summary

Do not inject inter-area routes into nssa

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

OSPF Router Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

 

 

no area <area_id> range <ip_address> <ip_address_mask> [ advertise | not-advertise | cost ]

None.

 

Syntax Description

no

Negate a command or set its defaults

area

OSPF area ID

<area_id>

The OSPF area ID can be specified as either an IPv4 address format(A.B.C.D) or a decimal value from 0 to 4294967295.

range

Summarize routes matching address range (ABRs only)

<ip_address>

IPv4 address

<ip_address_mask>

The wildcard-mask of the IPv4 address, where 0 is a match, and 1 is a 'do not care' bit.

advertise

Summarize intra area paths from the address range in one summary-LSA(Type-3) and advertised to other areas.

not-advertise

The intra area paths from the address range are not advertised to other areas.

cost

User specified cost (or metric) for this summary route.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

OSPF Router Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

Summarize routes matching address range (ABRs only)

<ipv6_subnet>

IPv6 Subnet

advertise

Summarize intra area paths from the address range in one summary-LSA (Type-3) and advertised to other areas. This option has no significance here.

not-advertise

The intra area paths from the address range are not advertised to other areas. This option has no significance here.

cost

User specified cost (or metric) for this summary route.

Clear the description for an IPMC profile

 

Syntax Description

no

Negate a command or set its defaults

description

Description of the profile (0-64 characters in ASCII range [32-126]).

 

Default

None

Command Mode

IPMC Profile Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When you are in IPMC profile configuration mode, use no description command to clear the additional description for a profile.

Example

This example shows when and how to execute no description command in ipmc profile configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# description This is a profile used for test

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

description This is a profile used for test

!

...

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# no description

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# exit

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

!

...

The switch remembers if an EAPOL frame has been received on the port for the life-time of the port. Once the switch considers whether to enter the Guest VLAN, it will first check if this option is enabled or disabled. If disabled (unchecked, default), the switch will only enter the Guest VLAN if an EAPOL frame has not been received on the port for the life-time of the port. If enabled (checked), the switch will consider entering the Guest VLAN even if an EAPOL frame has been received on the port for the life-time of the port.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

no ipmc profile

Default

IPMC profile filtering is disabled by default

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When the IPMC profile filtering is no longer required, use this command to disable the profile filtering.

Example

This example shows how to execute no ipmc profile command in global configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# do show running-config all-defaults

...

!

no ipmc profile

!

...

Switch(config)# ipmc profile

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc profile

!

...

Switch(config)# no ipmc profile

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

...

Switch(config)# do show running-config all-defaults

...

!

no ipmc profile

!

...

 

 

no ipmc profile { all | <profile_name> }

Delete a specific or all IPMC profiles

 

Syntax Description

no

Negate a command or set its defaults

ipmc

IPv4/IPv6 multicast configuration

profile

IPMC profile configuration

all

Delete all profiles

<profile_name>

Delete this particular profile

 

Default

None

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When the IPMC profile is no longer needed, use this command to delete the profile.

Example

This example shows how to execute no ipmc profile command in global configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# exit

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

...

Switch(config)# no ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

...

no lldp med type

##LLDP_ENDPOINT_HELP

 

Syntax Description

no

Use no, to set to default.

lldp

Link Layer Discover Protocol.

med

Media Endpoint Discovery.

type

Select if the interface is working as 'Network Connectivity Device' or an 'Endpoint Device'. The difference between working as 'Network Connectivity Device' and an 'Endpoint Device' is a question of who is initializing the LLDP-MED TLVs transmission. A 'Network Connectivity Device' is not starting LLDP-MED TLVs transmission until it has detected an 'Endpoint Device' as link partner. An 'Endpoint Device' will start LLDP-MED TLVs transmission at once.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

no range { all | <range_name> }

Delete a specific or all filtering rule in an IPMC profile

 

Syntax Description

no

Negate a command or set its defaults

range

A range of IPv4/IPv6 multicast addresses for the profile

all

Delete all ranges in this profile.

<range_name>

Delete this particular range in this profile.

 

Default

None

Command Mode

IPMC Profile Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When you are in IPMC profile configuration mode, use the no range command to remove a specific filtering rule.

Example

This example shows when and how to execute the no range command in IPMC profile configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

...

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# no range Video

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# exit

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

!

...

<diff>

Choose the maximum difference measured in number of packets

period

paths

<paths>

outer-tag { none | vid { { <vid> [ / <vid_mask> ] | any } [ pcp <pcp_val> [ / <pcp_mask> ] ] [ dei <dei_val> ] [ { c-tag | s-tag } ] } }

None.

 

Syntax Description

outer-tag

Configuration of an outer tag to match against incoming frames

none

The frame must be untagged

vid

The frame must be tagged. The next keyword tells whether all VLANs are matched or only a specific with an optional mask

<vid>

VLAN ID to match incoming frames against

/

Specify a mask. If no mask is specified, all bits of the VLAN ID shall match the incoming frame

<vid_mask>

A mask specified as an integer, that specifies which bits of the VLAN ID that shall match the incoming frames

any

Match any incoming VLAN ID

pcp

Configuration of a PCP value to match against incoming frames

<pcp_val>

The PCP value to match the incoming frames against

/

Configuration of a mask. If no mask is specified, all bits of the PCP value shall match the incoming frame

<pcp_mask>

A mask that specifies the bits of the PCP value that shall match the incoming frame

dei

Specify a DEI value to match the incoming frame against

<dei_val>

The DEI value that shall match the incoming frame

c-tag

If specified, only match C-tagged frames (EtherType = 0x8100)

s-tag

If specified, only match S-tagged frames (EtherType = 0x88a8)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

radius-server host <host_name> [ auth-port <auth_port> ] [ acct-port <acct_port> ] [ timeout <seconds> ] [ retransmit <retries> ] [ key { [ unencrypted ] <unencrypted_key> | encrypted <encrypted_key> } ]

Use the radius-server host command to add a new RADIUS host.

 

Syntax Description

radius-server

Configure RADIUS

host

Specify a RADIUS server

<host_name>

Hostname or IPv4/IPv6 address

auth-port

UDP port for RADIUS authentication server

<auth_port>

UDP port number or 0 to disable authentication

acct-port

UDP port for RADIUS accounting server

<acct_port>

UDP port number or 0 to disable accounting

timeout

Time to wait for this RADIUS server to reply (overrides default)

<seconds>

Wait time in seconds

retransmit

Specify the number of retries to active server (overrides default)

<retries>

Number of retries for a transaction

key

Server specific key (overrides default)

unencrypted

Specifies an UNENCRYPTED secret key will follow

<unencrypted_key>

The UNENCRYPTED (Plain Text) secret key. Notice that you have no chance to get the Plain Text secret key after this command. The system will always display the ENCRYPTED password.

encrypted

Specifies an ENCRYPTED secret key will follow

<encrypted_key>

The ENCRYPTED (hidden) secret key. Notice the ENCRYPTED secret key will be decoded by system internally. You cannot directly use it as same as the Plain Text and it is not human-readable text normally.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

range <range_name> { permit | deny } [ log ] [ next <next_range_name> ]

Create or update a filtering rule in an IPMC profile

 

Syntax Description

range

A range of IPv4/IPv6 multicast addresses for the profile

<range_name>

Name of existing IPMC range to use in this profile

permit

Permit matching addresses

deny

Deny matching addresses

log

Log when matching

next

To insert this rule a specific place in this profile's list, write the name of the range to insert it just before. If left out, this new rule will be added last.

<next_range_name>

Name of range (1-16 characters in ASCII range [33-126]. Cannot be 'all' (case-insensitively))

 

Default

Logging disabled and deny matching addresses

Command Mode

IPMC Profile Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

When you are in IPMC profile configuration mode, use range command to include a specific condition for filtering.

Example

This example shows when and how to execute range command in ipmc profile configuration mode:

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit log

!

...

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# exit

Switch(config)# do show running-config

...

!

ipmc range Video 230.0.0.0 230.0.0.255

!

ipmc profile EXAMPLE

range Video permit

!

...

ring-type { major | sub-ring [ virtual-channel ] | interconnected-sub-ring { connected-ring <connected_ring_inst> [ virtual-channel ] [ propagate-topology-change ] } }

##HELP_ERPS_RING_TYPE

 

Syntax Description

ring-type

Controls whether this is a major ring or a sub-ring. Only major rings are supported if using G.8032v1.

major

Make this a major ring, which always has two ring ports

sub-ring

Make this a non-interconnected sub-ring, which has two ring ports

virtual-channel

Configure this sub-ring with a R-APS virtual channel, that is, R-APS PDUs are not forwarded between ring-port links if one end is blocked

interconnected-sub-ring

Make this an interconnected sub-ring, which has only one ring port (port0), but connects to a major ring

connected-ring

An interconnected sub-ring points to another ring with two ring ports (that is, that other ring cannot itself be an interconnected sub-ring), which receives flush notifications and may carry R-APS PDUs for the sub-ring

<connected_ring_inst>

The ERPS instance number of the connected ring that this interconnected sub-ring connects to

virtual-channel

Configure this interconnected sub-ring with a R-APS virtual channel, that is, R-APS PDUs are transmitted on the connected ring that this sub-ring connects to

propagate-topology-change

If a topology-change occurs on this interconnected sub-ring, the connected ring also flushes its FDB. If this keyword is specified, the connected ring will also send Flush R-APS Event PDU onto its ring ports

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

ERPS Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_ERPS_RING_TYPE

Example

None.

 

 

rmon alarm <id> { ifInOctets | ifInUcastPkts | ifInNUcastPkts | ifInDiscards | ifInErrors | ifInUnknownProtos | ifOutOctets | ifOutUcastPkts | ifOutNUcastPkts | ifOutDiscards | ifOutErrors | ifOutQLen } <ifIndex> <interval> { absolute | delta } rising-threshold <rising_threshold> <rising_event_id> falling-threshold <falling_threshold> <falling_event_id> { [ rising | falling | both ] }

None.

 

Syntax Description

rmon

Remote Monitoring

alarm

Configure an RMON alarm

<id>

Alarm entry ID

ifInOctets

The total number of octets received on the interface, including framing characters

ifInUcastPkts

The number of unicast packets delivered to a higher-layer protocol

ifInNUcastPkts

The number of broadcast and multicast packets delivered to a higher-layer protocol

ifInDiscards

The number of inbound packets that are discarded even the packets are normal

ifInErrors

The number of inbound packets that contained errors preventing them from being deliverable to a higher-layer protocol

ifInUnknownProtos

The number of the inbound packets that were discarded because of the unknown or unsupported protocol

ifOutOctets

The number of octets transmitted out of the interface, including framing characters

ifOutUcastPkts

The number of unicast packets that request to transmit

ifOutNUcastPkts

The number of broadcast and multicast packets that request to transmit

ifOutDiscards

The number of outbound packets that are discarded event the packets is normal

ifOutErrors

The number of outbound packets that could not be transmitted because of errors

ifOutQLen

The length of the output packet queue (in packets)

<ifIndex>

Interface index

<interval>

Sample interval

absolute

Test each sample directly

delta

Test delta between samples

rising-threshold

Configure the rising threshold

<rising_threshold>

rising threshold value

<rising_event_id>

Event to fire on rising threshold crossing. If this value is zero, no associated event will be generated, as zero is not a valid event index.

falling-threshold

Configure the falling threshold

<falling_threshold>

falling threshold value

<falling_event_id>

Event to fire on falling threshold crossing. If this value is zero, no associated event will be generated, as zero is not a valid event index.

rising

Trigger alarm when the first value is larger than the rising threshold

falling

Trigger alarm when the first value is less than the falling threshold

both

Trigger alarm when the first value is larger than the rising threshold or less than the falling threshold (default)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

show access-list ace-status [ static ] [ link-oam ] [ loop-protect ] [ dhcp ] [ dhcp6-snooping ] [ ptp ] [ upnp ] [ arp-inspection ] [ cfm ] [ aps ] [ erps ] [ mrp ] [ redbox ] [ ipmc ] [ ip-source-guard ] [ ipv6-source-guard ] [ ip-mgmt ] [ ztp ] [ ip ] [ conflicts ] [ switch <switch_list> ]

Use the show access-list ace-status privilege EXEC command without keywords to display the access-list ace status for all access-list users, or particularly the access-list user for the access-list ace status. Use conflicts keyword to display the access-list ace that doesn't apply on on the hardware.In other word, it means the specific ACE is not applied to the hardware due to hardware limitations.

Note: The parameter of access-list users is depended on these features if supported on the platform.

 

Syntax Description

show

Show running system information

access-list

Access list

ace-status

The local ACEs status

static

The ACEs that are configured by users manually

link-oam

The ACEs that are configured by Link OAM module

loop-protect

The ACEs that are configured by Loop Protect module

dhcp

The ACEs that are configured by DHCP module

dhcp6-snooping

The ACEs that are configured by DHCPv6 Snooping module

ptp

The ACEs that are configured by PTP module

upnp

The ACEs that are configured by UPnP module

arp-inspection

The ACEs that are configured by ARP Inspection module

cfm

The ACEs that are configured by CFM module

aps

The ACEs that are configured by APS module

erps

The ACEs that are configured by ERPS module

mrp

The ACEs that are configured by MRP module

redbox

The ACEs that are configured by RedBox module

ipmc

The ACEs that are configured by IPMC module

ip-source-guard

The ACEs that are configured by IP Source Guard module

ipv6-source-guard

The ACEs that are configured by IPv6 Source Guard module

ip-mgmt

The ACEs that are configured by IP Management module

ztp

The ACEs that are configured by ZTP module

ip

The ACEs that are configured by IP module

conflicts

The ACEs that did not get applied to the hardware due to hardware limitations

switch

Switch

<switch_list>

List of switch ID, ex, 1,3-5,6

 

Default

None.

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

show ip dhcp detailed statistics { server | client | snooping | relay | normal-forward | combined } [ interface <port_type> [ <in_port_list> ] ]

Use the show ip dhcp detailed statistics user EXEC command to display statistics. Notice that the normal forward per-port TX statistics isn't increased if the incoming DHCP packet is done by L3 forwarding mechanism. Notice that the normal forward per-port TX statistics isn't increased if the incoming DHCP packet is done by L3 forwarding mechanism.

Show running system information

detailed

statistics

Traffic statistics

server

client

DHCP client

DHCP snooping

relay

DHCP relay

normal-forward

combined

interface

Select an interface to configure

<port_type>

<in_port_list>

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

0

Usage Guideline

show ipmc profile [ name <name> ] [ details ]

This privileged execution command displays the settings for entire IPMC profile ranges or for a specific IPMC profile range

 

Syntax Description

show

None.

ipmc

None.

profile

None.

name

None.

<name>

None.

details

None.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Check the existing IPMC profile range settings

Example

These examples give the outputs from the show ipmc profile range command, with or without specifying a range identification.

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Audio ff3e::1234 ff3e::2234

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

Switch(config)# ipmc profile EXAMPLE

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# description A profile

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Video permit

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# range Audio deny log

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show ipmc profile name EXAMPLE

Profile Name Range Name Permit Log Start Address End Address

---------------- ---------------- ------ --- --------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------

EXAMPLE Video Yes No 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

Audio No Yes ff3e::1234 ff3e::2234

Switch(config-ipmc-profile)# do show ipmc profile name EXAMPLE details

Profile Name Range Name Permit Log Start Address End Address

---------------- ---------------- ------ --- --------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------

EXAMPLE <Default> No No 224.0.0.0 226.1.2.2

Video Yes No 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

<Default> No No 226.2.2.4 239.255.255.255

<Default> No No ff00:: ff3e::1233

Audio No Yes ff3e::1234 ff3e::2234

<Default> No No ff3e::2235 ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff:ffff

 

 

show ipmc range [ <range_name> ]

This privileged execution command displays the settings for entire IPMC profile ranges or for a specific IPMC profile range

 

Syntax Description

show

None.

ipmc

None.

range

None.

<range_name>

None.

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Check the existing IPMC profile range settings

Example

These examples give the outputs from the show ipmc profile range command, with or without specifying a range name.

Switch# configure terminal

Switch(config)# ipmc range Audio ff3e::1234 ff3e::2234

Switch(config)# ipmc range Video 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

Switch(config)# exit

Switch# show ipmc range

Range Name Start Address End Address

---------------- --------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------

Audio ff3e::1234 ff3e::2234

Video 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

Switch# show ipmc range Data

% Range Data does not exist

Switch# show ipmc range Video

# show ipmc range Video

Range Name Start Address End Address

---------------- --------------------------------------- ---------------------------------------

Video 226.1.2.3 226.2.2.3

show logging [ informational ] [ notice ] [ warning ] [ error ]

Use the show logging privileged EXEC command without keywords to display the logging configuration, or particularly the logging message summary for the logging level.

 

Syntax Description

show

Show running system information

logging

System logging message

informational

Severity 6: Informational messages

notice

Severity 5: Normal but significant condition

warning

Severity 4: Warning conditions

error

Severity 3: Error conditions

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Expressions are case sensitive. For example, if you enter | exclude output, the lines that contain output do not appear, but the lines that contain Output appear.

Example

This is an example of output from the show logging command:

Switch# show logging

Switch logging host mode is disabled

Switch logging host address is null

Switch logging level is informational

Number of entries:

Error : 1

Warning : 0

Notice : 0

Info. : 1

All : 2

ID Level Time & Message

-- ----- --------------

1 Info. 1970-01-01T00:00:00+00:00

Switch just made a cool boot.

2 Error 1970-01-01T00:00:05+00:00

LINK-UPDOWN: Interface GigabitEthernet 1/1, chan

ged state to up.

show redbox [ <inst_list> ] { status [ details ] | statistics [ details ] | nodes-table [ details [ filter ] | supervision [ filter ] ] | proxy-node-table [ details [ filter ] ] }

##HELP_SHOW_REDBOX

 

Syntax Description

show

Show the state or counters of one or more RedBox instances

redbox

Redundancy Box for PRP/HSR (IEC 62439-3)

<inst_list>

List of RedBox instances to show status, table contents or statistics for. If left out, all created RedBox instances will be shown

status

Show status

details

Show detailed status

statistics

Show statistics

details

Show detailed statistics

nodes-table

Show NodesTable

details

Show detailed NodesTable data contents

filter

Only show NodesTable data contents for entries that have non-zero 'Rx Wrong LAN'

supervision

Show detailed NodesTable supervision contents

filter

Only show NodesTable supervision contents for entries that have non-zero 'Rx Wrong LAN'

proxy-node-table

ProxyNodeTable contents

details

Show detailed ProxyNodeTable contents

filter

Only show ProxyNodeTable entries that have non-zero 'Rx Wrong LAN'

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

User EXEC Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_SHOW_REDBOX

Example

None.

smac { <mac_addr> [ / <mask_mac_addr> ] | any }

None.

 

Syntax Description

smac

Specify a source MAC mask to match against incoming frames

<mac_addr>

A source MAC address to match against incoming frames

/

Specify a mask. If no mask is specified, all bits of the source MAC address shall match the incoming frame

<mask_mac_addr>

A mask in the form xx:xx:xx:xx:xx:xx, that specifies which bits of the source MAC address that shall match the incoming frames. Default is to match all 48 bits

any

Match any source mac address

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.

 

 

snap { <oui> | rfc-1042 | snap-8021h } <pid>

None.

 

Syntax Description

snap

Match Subnetwork Access Protocol (SNAP) frames, i.e. frames with EtherType/TypeLength field less than 0x600 and DSAP = 0xaa and SSAP = 0xAA and Control field = 0x03

<oui>

SNAP OUI (Range 0x000000 - 0XFFFFFF)

rfc-1042

SNAP OUI is speficied in RFC1042, that is, 00:00:00

snap-8021h

SNAP OUI is specified in 802.1H, that is, 00:00:F8

<pid>

Protocol ID (Range: 0x0 - 0xFFFF). If OUI is all-zeros (rfc-1042), then this must be a valid EtherType (>= 0x600)

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Stream Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

None.
