speed { 10 | 100 | 1000 | 2500 | 5g | 10g | 25g | force-clause-73 | auto { [ 10 ] [ 100 ] [ 1000 ] [ 2500 ] [ 5g ] [ 10g ] { [ no-hdx ] | [ no-fdx ] } } }

##PORT_SPEED_HELP

 

Syntax Description

speed

Configures interface speed. If you use 10, 100, 1000 or one of the other keywords with the auto keyword the port will only advertise the specified speeds.

10

Force 10 Mbps

100

Force 100 Mbps

1000

Force 1000 Mbps

2500

Force 2500 Mbps

5g

Force 5 Gbps

10g

Force 10 Gbps

25g

Force 25 Gbps

force-clause-73

Force clause 73 even on Fiber SFPs

auto

Let the switch application decide whether to run aneg or a fixed speed - depending on port type and/or SFP transceiver types.

10

Advertise 10 Mbps

100

Advertise 100 Mbps

1000

Advertise 1000 Mbps

2500

Advertise 2500 Mbps

5g

Advertise 5 Gbps

10g

Advertise 10 Gbps

no-hdx

Only advertise full duplex, not half duplex.

no-fdx

Only adverties half duplex, not full duplex

 

Default

Speed is auto.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##PORT_SPEED_HELP

Example

svl fid <fid> vlan <vlan_list>

Shared VLAN Learning (SVL) makes it possible to learn multiple VLANs (VIDs) on the same FID. MAC addresses that get classified to a given VID will be mapped to its FID and learned on that FID.

 

Syntax Description

svl

Shared VLAN Learning

fid

Filter ID keyword

<fid>

Filter ID

vlan

VLAN keyword

<vlan_list>

VLAN List

 

Default

The no-form of this command changes all VIDs currently mapped to the FID back to being independent (IVL).

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

None.

Example

Let VID 2, 4 and 20-200 map to the same shared VLAN, 13 (notice that VID 13 by default is member of FID 13), so that the whole range will become 2,4,13,20-200):

(config)# svl fid 13 vlan 2,4,20-200

A given VID can only be mapped to one single FID.

Verify your settings with 'show svl'

 

 

switchport access vlan <pvid>

Use the switchport access vlan command to configure a port to a VLAN.

 

Syntax Description

switchport

Set VLAN switching mode characteristics

access

Set access mode characteristics of the interface

vlan

Set VLAN when interface is in access mode

<pvid>

VLAN ID of the VLAN when this port is in access mode

 

Default

The no switchport access command resets the access mode VLAN to the appropriate default VLAN.

Command Mode

Port List Interface Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

This command configures the Port VLAN ID (PVID) of an access port.

Example

This example shows to configure a PVID of an access port.

Switch(config-if)#switchport access vlan 2

You can verify your settings by entering the show vlan privileged EXEC command.

##HELP_FRER_RESET

 

Syntax Description

frer

Frame Replication and Elimination for Reliability (802.1CB)

reset

If latent-error is not specified: In generation mode, this resets the sequence counter. In recovery mode, this resets all recovery algorithms for this FRER instance

latent-error

This resets a possible (sticky) latent error signal in recovery mode with latent-error-detection enabled

 

Default

None.

User EXEC Mode

Set UDLD mode Normal or Aggressive on an interface

 

Syntax Description

udld

UDLD configurations.

port

UDLD configuration on the interface

aggressive

Enable UDLD in the aggressive mode on an interface

message

Configures the period of time between UDLD probe messages on ports that are in the advertisement phase and are determined to be bidirectional. The range is from 7 to 90 seconds (Currently default message time interval 7 sec is supported).

time-interval

Configures the period of time between UDLD probe messages on ports that are in the advertisement phase and are determined to be bidirectional. The range is from 7 to 90 seconds (Currently default message time interval 7 sec is supported).

<v_interval>

Configures the period of time between UDLD probe messages on ports that are in the advertisement phase and are determined to be bidirectional. The range is from 7 to 90 seconds (Currently default message time interval 7 sec is supported).

 

Default

UDLD mode is nornal

Command Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

username { default-administrator | <input_username> } privilege <priv> password { unencrypted <unencry_password> | encrypted <encry_password> | none }

Use the username <username> privilege <level> password encrypted <password> global configuration command to add a user with unencrypted password for the local switch access.

Use the username <username> privilege <level> password encrypted <password> global configuration command to add a user with encrypted password for the local switch access.

Use the username <username> privilege <level> password none global configuration command to remove the password for specific username.

 

Syntax Description

username

Establish User Name Authentication

default-administrator

default-administrator

<input_username>

User name allows letters, numbers and underscores

privilege

Set user privilege level

<priv>

User privilege level

password

Specify the password for the user

unencrypted

Specifies an UNENCRYPTED password will follow

<unencry_password>

The UNENCRYPTED (Plain Text) user password. Any printable characters including space is accepted. Notice that you have no chance to get the Plain Text password after this command. The system will always display the ENCRYPTED password.

encrypted

Specifies an ENCRYPTED password will follow

<encry_password>

The ENCRYPTED (hidden) user password. Notice the ENCRYPTED password will be decoded by system internally. You cannot directly use it as same as the Plain Text and it is not human-readable text normally.

none

NULL password

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

Global Configuration Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

Add a user for the local switch access.

Example

This example shows how to add a user named usertest with unencrypted password of testuser:

Switch(config)# username testuser privilege 5 password unencrypted testuser

You can verify your settings by entering the show running-config privileged EXEC command.

This example shows how to add a user named usertest with encrypted password of testuser:

Switch(config)# username testuser privilege 5 password encrypted dGVzdHVzZXI=

You can verify your settings by entering the show running-config privileged EXEC command.

This example shows how to remove the password for username testuser:

Switch(config)# no username testuser privilege 5 password none

You can verify your settings by entering the show running-config privileged EXEC command.

None.

 

 

working sf-trigger { link | { mep domain <md_name> service <ma_name> mep-id <mepid> } }

##HELP_APS_WORKING_SF_TRIGGER

 

Syntax Description

working

Working port configuration

sf-trigger

Choose whether the working port's interface link state or a MEP installed on working's interface is used as signal-fail trigger

link

Working interface link state is used as signal-fail trigger

mep

A MEP installed on working interface is used as signal-fail trigger

domain

The MEP's domain

<md_name>

The MEP's domain name

service

The MEP's service within the domain

<ma_name>

The MEP's service name within the domain

mep-id

The MEP's MEP-ID

<mepid>

The MEP's MEP-ID

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

APS Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_APS_WORKING_SF_TRIGGER

Example

None.

 

 

working-mep domain <md_name> service <ma_name> mep-id <mepid>

##HELP_APS_WORKING_MEP

 

Syntax Description

working-mep

Specify which MEP provides signal-fail for the working port.

domain

The working MEP's domain

<md_name>

The working MEP's domain name

service

The working MEP's service within the domain

<ma_name>

The working MEP's service name within the domain

mep-id

The working MEP's MEP-ID

<mepid>

The working MEP's MEP-ID

 

Default

None.

Command Mode

APS Mode

Privilege Level

15

Usage Guideline

##HELP_APS_WORKING_MEP

Example

None.
